TY  - JOUR
T1  - PERCEIVED LEADER BEHAVIOR AS A FUNCTION OF THE LEADER'S INTERPERSONAL TRUST ORIENTATION
AU  - Sgro, Joseph A.
AU  - Worchel, Philip
AU  - Pence, Earl C.
AU  - Orban, Joseph A.
Y1  - 1980/03/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255504
DO  - 10.5465/255504
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 161
EP  - 165
VL  - 23
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents the results of a study designed to measure leadership behavior as a function of leaders' interpersonal trust orientation. According to the study, leader interpersonal trust is a variable that could possibly affect the way in which subordinates perceive the behavior of leaders. Using as an instrument the Ohio State Leader Behavior Description Questionnaire and the complete Job Descriptive Index, the study determined that leader interpersonal trust is related to consideration and tolerance of freedom.
AB  - The article presents the results of a study designed to measure leadership behavior as a function of leaders' interpersonal trust orientation. According to the study, leader interpersonal trust is a variable that could possibly affect the way in which subordinates perceive the behavior of leaders. Using as an instrument the Ohio State Leader Behavior Description Questionnaire and the complete Job Descriptive Index, the study determined that leader interpersonal trust is related to consideration and tolerance of freedom.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255504
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255504
