T1  - A COMPARISON OF LEVELS OF JOB SATISFACTION, ROLE STRESS, AND PERSONAL COMPETENCE BETWEEN UNION MEMBERS AND NONMEMBERS
AU  - Odewahn, Charles A.
AU  - Petty, M.M.
Y1  - 1980/03/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255502
DO  - 10.5465/255502
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 150
EP  - 155
VL  - 23
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The study examines the affect of labor union membership on a number of factors including job stress, job satisfaction, self-esteem and employee competence. According to the results of the study, there was a significant reported difference between union members and nonmembers in regards to formal education, organizational tenure and position tenure. The study asserts that union members experience lower levels of job satisfaction, job stress and also display lower levels of personal competence than do nonmembers.
AB  - The study examines the affect of labor union membership on a number of factors including job stress, job satisfaction, self-esteem and employee competence. According to the results of the study, there was a significant reported difference between union members and nonmembers in regards to formal education, organizational tenure and position tenure. The study asserts that union members experience lower levels of job satisfaction, job stress and also display lower levels of personal competence than do nonmembers.
